On july 9, 2013
Hacksaw

It's situational. One friend in class gives you an extra turn (11 instead of 10) and two friends in class gives you two extra turns (12 instead of 10), so you get a little more time to defeat all the students, but depending on how long it takes you to knock one out it may not be enough.

My last mission I just finished in three classes. First class has the first friend show up, so 7 students, and pretty sure I had them all defeated with 5 turns remaining (which would be pure luck, usually only have 1 or 2 turns remaining). Second class has the second friend show up and beat all 8 students with 1 turn remaining, and last class I was only able to beat 7 of 8. Still made all objectives, so only lost a couple of XP points.

As with all Motion Twin games you are ultimately bound by a random number generator (this one selecting your available attacks for a turn), so if you get screwed there it'll hardly matter how many students you have, otherwise it's all making the best choices with the available resources you have, those resources being Budget , Ferrier , sponges, twinoids, and teacher's pet abilities. Budget mainly maatters for recharging the other three expendable resources (and usually better to buy in bulk if you can).

Don't let the "timer" scare you, it's only counting down a number of turns, take all the time you need on each turn.

TradeFederation
shadowlakeDo pupils help more or harm more? I can see they give you bonus missions but doesn't it also mean there are more students in your class to defeat?

I had to play through a few missions to completion, but I can now say that bonus students are almost always a plus. You don't actually need to defeat all the students in a class to 'win'. You get a proportional amount of XP to the number of defeated students, so more students can only help that, since there appears to be no penalty for not defeating a student, except that you cannot convert extra turns into XP. The conversion rate is only 1 turn = 1 XP, so you are way better off taking out another student than getting XP from extra turns. The amount of budget you get from finishing a class is actually random, I've gotten more budget from only defeating 4 students than i got from taking out 6 of them, so more students don't help or hurt on that.


The big plus is the bonus student mission prize. This is random, but it is usually pretty good. My last two sent students gave me 22 coin for one, and 14 XP for the other. The coin was more than i usually get for a single class, and my main quest only gave me 40 XP for completing it, so I came out way ahead with the extra 14 XP a single sent student tacked on to that.


If you are getting guest students, I suggest you always choose the row or column powers if you see them when you level up, since more students means more targets for the area of effect teachings. Plus, you can mega boost those types of attacks with twinoids, if you are into using them.
On july 9, 2013
npfan
TradeFederationYou get a proportional amount of XP to the number of defeated students, so more students can only help that, since there appears to be no penalty for not defeating a student, except that you cannot convert extra turns into XP.

However, if you don't defeat the student, you lose the opportunity to gain more XP. More students would help in terms of XP if you could defeat them, and that can sometimes be a big 'if'.

TradeFederationThe conversion rate is only 1 turn = 1 XP, so you are way better off taking out another student than getting XP from extra turns.

You don't choose between gaining more XP from extra turns and defeating pupils. You defeat pupils as soon as possible to get extra XP from leftover turns. If you can't defeat the whole class, you defeat as many pupils as possible. Since you have nothing to lose from trying to defeat the whole class (unless you want to manipulate scores in such a way so that you hold off completing the primary mission to complete secondary missions) and you have to take out students anyway to reach that goals, the notion you are 'better off' doesn't make sense.

TradeFederationThe big plus is the bonus student mission prize. This is random, but it is usually pretty good. My last two sent students gave me 22 coin for one, and 14 XP for the other. The coin was more than i usually get for a single class, and my main quest only gave me 40 XP for completing it, so I came out way ahead with the extra 14 XP a single sent student tacked on to that.

I agree that the budget bonus is nice when you defeat certain students sent by friends. A major problem though is that I sometimes have to delay completing the primary mission to complete the secondary missions, so spending the time to defeat the guest student may not be worth it. For example, I completed a 70 XP missions in two classes, while the secondary mission required me to either spend all four classes and spend two intermissions correcting papers instead of replenishing SC or spend five classes and then gain only 35 XP from the primary mission.

Ultimately, it comes down to luck. Pupils sent from users can either help you or hurt you.

It appears pupil-sending is now a little buggy.

To send a pupil now you have to go to the Ranking page through the link at the top of the page, then click the Choose friend button (next to the message telling you how many students you have left to send) and choose a friend from your list in the pop-up screen that shows up. This is also where you choose which item (if any) you want to send with the pupil.

Clicking Send pupil on another person's home page will only bring you to your own home page now, and won't send the pupil (it seems) even if they are your friend.

All that now being said, just started a new mission, so can fit one student into my queue now and another in a few hours.

Hacksaw
Qazplm632Click on username, then Teachers Story profile and there is an option Send a pupil

Except that it's currently broken.

Two ways to do it. First is to go to either Your Home or Rankings, click Choose a Friend at the top of the web page, and then choose one of the friends listed. Note that friends on this screen are sorted numerically by Twinoid ID number and you can only see a maximum of 73 friends at time of this posting.

The other option is to use a trick coro made a quick tutorial for HERE. What you need to do is go into console view for your browser and put in the command chooseFriend(######); where ###### is replaced by the recipient's Twinoid ID number.

Kompera
digimostrosI don't know what sending pupils is about. Can someone send me one to figure out ?.

When a friend sends you a pupil you will have an additional pupil arrive in class after the first turn. This pupil will have your friends' name. Otherwise, aside from the single lost turn with the pupil in the class, they operate under the same conditions as other pupils, including needing to meet a specific or a minimum score to complete the mission.

If you have two friends' pupils in your queue, the second one shows up after the first turn in the second class of the mission.

Typically the lost class and turns don't matter except for minimum score missions, where you'll have to raise your friends' pupils to meet the mission minimum.

Friends' pupils can help you achieve mission goals such as 'X number of Score Y pupils', and they can add to your experience earned in a class since you earn one EXP per pupil beaten. They may also make it more difficult to get a 'perfect class' (all pupils beaten) since they add to the number of pupils you need to beat.

There is no EXP award for a perfect class, so all you risk losing is the discount to going immediately into your next class without having to wait for the timer to expire.
On september 24, 2013
Hacksaw
KomperaThere is no EXP award for a perfect class, so all you risk losing is the discount to going immediately into your next class without having to wait for the timer to expire.

Actually, there is. You get 1 bonus for each turn remaining at the end of the class if you beat all the students. You also get a discount of -5 off the cost of skipping the timer between classes for each turn remaining, and +3 points on the leaderboards (if you care about that) for each turn remaining.

Also, what do you mean by "lost class"? You don't lose any classes for having friends sent, If anything, you gain an extra class with which to beat the mission "on time" for each friend student.

GhostAlso, what do you mean by "lost class"? You don't lose any classes for having friends sent, If anything, you gain an extra class with which to beat the mission "on time" for each friend student.

By "lost class and turns" I am referring to the fact that the first friends' pupil shows up after the first turn of the first class in a mission (assuming your queue is full at the start of the mission), so that's a turn lost. The second friends' pupil shows up after the first turn of the second class.

So that's one turn lost for the first friends' pupil, and one class and one turn lost for the second friends' pupil. From the perspective of your time available to defeat those pupils and raise their scores.

ShuDog

The referral link keeps getting posted because the term used in both cases is "friends" and it's not immediately obvious how to add friends.

This is not necessary now for sending pupils, but it is a ton easier to have a drop-down list. If you don't want to keep typing people's names:
From this post, you can click people's names. The pop-up box will include "Add Contact".
On the way way top right, mouse-over your username. A panel slides out.
Among the icons is Contacts. Click to manage contacts. Another pop-up box.
To see who has added you, click the tab on top of that box.

When sending pupils, (From "Your Home" You have _ pupils remaining to send to your friends today! Choose a friend), click the little dude in step 2., and your Contacts list will pop out. *One* click on a name selects a Contact to receive students.

Hope that helps the new guys.

ShuDog

Repost, since I'm gathering a few contacts who have not added me back... and thus they are always last to get pupils from me.

This is not necessary now for sending pupils, but it is a ton easier to have a drop-down list. If you don't want to keep typing people's names:
From this post, you can click people's names. The pop-up box will include "Add Contact".
On the way way top right, mouse-over your username. A panel slides out.
Among the icons is Contacts. Click to manage contacts. Another pop-up box.
To see who has added you, click the tab on top of that box.

When sending pupils,
(From "Your Home" and "Ranking" You have # pupils remaining to send to your friends today! Choose a friend; from "Play" it's the Send a Pupil button on the bottom left),
in the pop up box, click the little dude in step 2., and your Contacts list will expand. *One* click on a name selects a Contact to receive students. Only click an object beforehand if you want to send it to them.

Hope that helps the new guys.

Is this action one-time event, and I should send pupils constantly, or I can send pupil once, and he will appear every class, which leads by my contacts?

You can send up to three students per day. Each sent student will last for one mission (however many classes that takes), and then be gone. Each player can have up to two students per mission. So if you wish to have a steady stream of pupils, it's a good idea to keep sending them out.
